Without reliability, the product is likely to get recalled as well due to lawsuits be pressed from patients who had to deal with failures.

Each of the surfactants performed best in a certain category. For instance the hydrophilic surfactant performed best in reliability while the biological surfactant had the best blood cell reactivity

Here is my justification:

Used Phase Inversion because it wasn't the most expensive, and it had the highest initial flux rate, but had poor reliability. Hydrophilic surfactants and 2% CNT inclusion will help balance out the poor reliability of the manufacturing process.

The material is PSF because that is what our group is focused on. Vapor deposition polymerization and 4.0% inclusion gives the highest reliability rating. Also, the design has a hydrophilic surfactant because that one has the highest reliabiltiy and a low cost.

We chose the Phase Inversion process because it had the highest flux and lowest blood cell reactivity, which were both important aspects to Padma Rao. We chose the biological surfactant because it had the lowest reactivity of all of the different surfactants. We chose 1.5% nanotube because that resulted in the highest flux.

I used Dry-jet Wet because the cost was the lowest. I picked none for Surfactant because none had the lowest cost. The marketability Rudy wanted was to use nano tubes because it is new and appealing. I picked Nanotube % of 2.0 because it was in the middle of the others talked about in the group. Again no surfactant had a cost that varied that much.

The phase inversion process was chosen because this process resulted in the lowest blood cell reactivity. Biological surfactant was also chosen because the blood cell reactivity was the lowest with this surfactant.  The 1.5% CNT was chosen because the flux was the highest.
